itunesNotes.standard: Who has time to read these days? We do! That’s thanks to Blinkist’s brilliant summaries of top non-fiction books. Not only are the articles packed with insight into business, culture and self-improvement, they’re designed with busy schedules in mind. Seamless switching between text and narration is super-useful on the go, and finding topics couldn’t be simpler.
itunesNotes.short: Relatable bite-sized reads to help spark new ideas.

itunesNotes.standard: With its friendly approach and awesome updates, Duolingo’s long been one of our favorite apps for learning another language. Its secret: making the process genuinely fun. Engaging mini-games test your reading, writing, and speaking skills, and joining a club (where you can encourage and compete with others) adds a great social element. Bonus: all those languages and games are available for free!
itunesNotes.short: Learn a new language. Join a club, chat with bots, and get reminders to practice.

itunesNotes.standard: With Memrise, language learning’s a game—the irresistible kind that anyone can pick up and play. It teaches you everyday words and phrases—perfect for your next trip abroad—and reinforces them with fun quizzes and playful images. We get an awesome sense of progress every time we use it.
itunesNotes.short: Pick up a new language! Learn how to pronounce phrases from native speakers.

Tandem’s global community connects pre-screened learners and tutors through text and video chats, and it covers just about every spoken and written language—including Klingon, Dothraki and Emoji. ??????!

itunesNotes.standard: You’ve always promised yourself you’ll learn how to play piano one day. How about today? No need to hook up a special keyboard: Simply Piano listens to what you’re playing on any keyboard or piano—or lets you use an onscreen one. Within minutes you’ll start reading music, and soon you’ll be playing along with familiar songs and adopting good habits. Even if you’ve never touched a keyboard in your life, Simply Piano makes it easy to learn.

itunesNotes.standard: The Montessori education method was conceptualized at the start of the 20th century by an Italian pediatrician of the same name. The idea behind it is to offer children an education based on a sensory and kinetic way of learning. Montessori Preschool is based on this ideology and provides a variety of activities, which seek to guide children ages 3–7 as they embark on their first steps in the world of education.

itunesNotes.standard: Simply Guitar is all about you: your skills, your pace, and your comfort levels. No experience is needed—the app actually starts by asking if you even own a guitar—and after a few quick questions about your skill level and background, you’ll be on your way to learning with tracks like Queen’s “We Will Rock You,” Aretha Franklin’s “Chain of Fools,” and Billie Eilish’s “Bad Guy.” To help you grow your skills, Simply Guitar uses live feedback: It will recognize what you’re playing and provide real-time tips on your strum patterns and D chords. Start with basics, follow the lessons, and work your way up to power chords—you'll be playing lead guitar in no time.
itunesNotes.short: Strum away with step-by-step tutorials and get feedback right away.
